8.311 | Electromagnetic Theory | http://ocw.mit.edu/courses/physics/8-311-electromagnetic-theory-spring-2004 | textbook:Schwinger = Schwinger, Julian, L. L. DeRaad Jr., K. A. Milton, W-Y Tsai. Classical Electrodynamics. Reading, Massachusetts: Perseus Book Group, 1998. level:Graduate instructors:Leonid Levitov term:Spring 2004 features:Selected lecture notes, Assignments (no solutions), Exams and solutions description:Electromagnetic Theory covers the basic principles of electromagnetism: experimental basis, electrostatics, magnetic fields of steady currents, motional e.m.f. and electromagnetic induction, Maxwell's equations, propagation and radiation of electromagnetic waves, electric and magnetic properties of matter, and conservation laws. This is a graduate level subject which uses appropriate mathematics but whose emphasis is on physical phenomena and principles.
8.321 | Quantum Theory I | http://ocw.mit.edu/courses/physics/8-321-quantum-theory-i-fall-2002 | level:Graduate instructors:Washington Taylor term:Fall 2002 features:Lecture notes, Assignments (no solutions) description:8.321 is the first semester of a two-semester subject on quantum theory, stressing principles. Topics covered include: Hilbert spaces, observables, uncertainty relations, eigenvalue problems and methods for solution thereof, time-evolution in the Schrodinger, Heisenberg, and interaction pictures, connections between classical and quantum mechanics, path integrals, quantum mechanics in EM fields, angular momentum, time-independent perturbation theory, density operators, and quantum measurement.
8.322 | Quantum Theory II | http://ocw.mit.edu/courses/physics/8-322-quantum-theory-ii-spring-2003 | level:Graduate instructors:Washington Taylor term:Spring 2003 features:Lecture notes description:8.322 is the second semester of a two-semester subject on quantum theory, stressing principles.&nbsp;Topics covered include: time-dependent perturbation theory and applications to radiation, quantization of EM radiation field, adiabatic theorem and Berry's phase, symmetries in QM, many-particle systems, scattering theory, relativistic quantum mechanics, and Dirac equation.
8.323 | Relativistic Quantum Field Theory I | http://ocw.mit.edu/courses/physics/8-323-relativistic-quantum-field-theory-i-spring-2008 | textbook:Peskin, Michael E., and Daniel V. Schroeder. An Introduction to Quantum Field Theory. Boulder, CO: Westview Press, 1995. level:Graduate instructors:Alan Guth term:Spring 2008 features:Lecture notes, Assignments (no solutions) description:8.323, Relativistic Quantum Field Theory I, is a one-term self-contained subject in quantum field theory. Concepts and basic techniques are developed through applications in elementary particle physics, and condensed matter physics.
